One cannot compare scalped merchandise, creating false shortages to a good investment.  The long lines start outside of Sportsmans warehouse 2 hours before it opens, and the scalpers don't even let the merchandise hit the shelves.  That is NOT free trade.   I believe the SEC has rules against this type of insider trading.

We as consumers have the power.  If we don't buy, there is no market.  I have nothing against a person who prepares for the unexpected.  Kudos to you that do.   

Don't buy the overpriced stuff, and see how fast the "price drop" ads appear!

title: For Sale:  Free trade.. free to buy, or not buy
postcontent:
We consumers have the absolute power to buy, or NOT to buy whatever we choose.  '
Ammo scalping cannot be compared to a good investment.  Scalpers are creating a false sense of scarcity, then inflating prices.  (ammo producers still charge "normal" prices". )  I believe the SEC calls this "insider trading" and it is also illegal.  While the "scalpers" aren't necessarily doing anything illegal, I'm sure that many will agree that it is despicable and immoral.  

I commend those who prepare for the future.  stockpiling, hoarding, or whatever it is called may lead to good preparedness. 

 The choice NOT to buy this incredibly marked up product will send a message to those who are telling us what they think things cost.  

Do NOT buy their hype or products, and you will see how fast the "priced reduced" stuff will start showing up.  Ride out the storm.  I invite all intelligent comments.  Any other derogatory comments will go ignored.

$400.00 Firm.

Gun new was $665.00.

Less than 100 rounds fired. Has "Accutrigger" for a light but safe touch. Comes with case, and Nikon BDC ranging scope.

I do not know whether this has been fixed. We did scope the chamber and it looks clean. If it has not, it can be sent back to Savage for service under warranty and fixed (Turn around 3-4 weeks.) Or a local Gunsmith power hone it for $100 (Quote from Gunsmoke.)

So, here is the math:

If the chamber was fixed, you get a barely used rifle + scope + case for $265.00 off new.
If the chamber was not fixed, you get a barely used rifle + scope + case  for $165.00 off new.

Either way, it's a bargain.

title: For Sale:  AR-18 ArmaLite Tactical 5.56 .223, Factory scope
postcontent: This is one of only 4,018 produced in the United States. More about the AR 18/AR 180: Stamped steel and welded construction. Reliable and very accurate at all ranges up to 460 meters. Simple construction and very few parts. Gas piston operation is much more resistant to carbon fouling: Gas and carbon does not vent into the receiver (sound familiar?), so shotguns and AR 15s are just now catching up. Powered by a short-stroke gas piston above the barrel and unlike the AR-15, the cocking handle fits directly into a recess in the bolt carrier and reciprocates with it during firing, allowing the you to force the breech closed or open if necessary. Since the recoil springs are housed in the receiver, this has a side-folding stock. 2-position flip aperture rear sight and post foresight. Dovetail on the receiver fits the proprietary ArmaLite quick-detachable scope mount. The 180 uses what looks like AR mags, but the mag catch window is a 1/2" x 1/16" slot instead of the square window of the AR mag. AR mags will fit the 180's mag well, but will not latch unless that 1/2"x1/16" window is cut/milled/ground into them.
